TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Religious Manager
AU  - Senger, John
Y1  - 1970/06/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255104
DO  - 10.5465/255104
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 179
EP  - 186
VL  - 13
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Managers' choice of goals, their rating of subordinates, and various organizational and biographical data were related to the managers' Religion Value score as measured by judging religious terms against semantic differential scales. Broadly, the more religious managers were found to be more socially and humanistically oriented and relatively disinterested in personal earnings and company profits. They appeared to be less ?self-actualizing.? The managers with high Religion Value scores tended to be most frequently in marketing, to have studied business administration, to be generally less well educated, to tend to come from lower classes, to participate in community and professional activities, to engage in active rather than sedentary hobbies, to be higher rated in all-around competence, but not to hold the top position in the company.
AB  - Managers' choice of goals, their rating of subordinates, and various organizational and biographical data were related to the managers' Religion Value score as measured by judging religious terms against semantic differential scales. Broadly, the more religious managers were found to be more socially and humanistically oriented and relatively disinterested in personal earnings and company profits. They appeared to be less ?self-actualizing.? The managers with high Religion Value scores tended to be most frequently in marketing, to have studied business administration, to be generally less well educated, to tend to come from lower classes, to participate in community and professional activities, to engage in active rather than sedentary hobbies, to be higher rated in all-around competence, but not to hold the top position in the company.
