TY  - JOUR
T1  - “Culture” And Other Explanatory Variables In Comparative Management Studies
AU  - Ajiferuke, Musbau
AU  - Boddewyn, J.
Y1  - 1970/06/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255102
DO  - 10.5465/255102
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 153
EP  - 163
VL  - 13
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A partial survey of the literature of comparative management reveals that there are four major types of explanation of managerial similarities and differences: cultural, economic, psychological, and sociological. Cultural types predominate, but they are generally imprecise regarding the nature and influence of culture; this reduces their credibility. Meanwhile, their popularity reflects the basic assumption that in cross-cultural research, culture is the independent variable.
AB  - A partial survey of the literature of comparative management reveals that there are four major types of explanation of managerial similarities and differences: cultural, economic, psychological, and sociological. Cultural types predominate, but they are generally imprecise regarding the nature and influence of culture; this reduces their credibility. Meanwhile, their popularity reflects the basic assumption that in cross-cultural research, culture is the independent variable.
