TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technological Forecasting In The Decision Process
AU  - Roman, Daniel D.
Y1  - 1970/06/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255100
DO  - 10.5465/255100
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 127
EP  - 138
VL  - 13
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Technological forecasting, as distinct from general forecasting activity, has been described as ?the probabilistic assessment, on a relatively high confidence level, of future technology transfer.? The foundation underlying technological forecasting is that many futures can be achieved, the route to these occurrences can be determined and management through the process of identification within a discernable time frame can divert resources to facilitate the accomplishment of future objectives. Technological forecasting as a management concept is relatively new. It represents an organized approach to selective search for information. It can be useful in deriving strategy to guide planning, programming, authorization, implementation, control and evaluation.
AB  - Technological forecasting, as distinct from general forecasting activity, has been described as ?the probabilistic assessment, on a relatively high confidence level, of future technology transfer.? The foundation underlying technological forecasting is that many futures can be achieved, the route to these occurrences can be determined and management through the process of identification within a discernable time frame can divert resources to facilitate the accomplishment of future objectives. Technological forecasting as a management concept is relatively new. It represents an organized approach to selective search for information. It can be useful in deriving strategy to guide planning, programming, authorization, implementation, control and evaluation.
